The order 
Geophilomorpha
is considered one of the most diverse groups within 
Chilopoda
due to a combination of major apomorphic features and life history (e.g. 

; 

; 

, 

). One of the most noticeable features that contribute to great diversity of geophilomorphs is a greater number of leg-bearing segments (27 to 191; always an odd number) than in other centipedes, with the exception of the most polypodous scolopendromorph 

Scolopendropsis duplicata
Chagas-Junior, Edgecombe & Minelli, 2008

(with the 39 and 43 leg-bearing segments; see additionally Chagas-Jr. 
et al
. 2023). In 
Geophilomorpha
, the number of leg-bearing segments often varies within species and is usually fewer in males than in females (

). So far, about 1250 species have been described and classified within 13 families (

). Among them, there are only five species with less than 31 leg-bearing segments, two of them from the family 
Schendylidae
and three from the family 
Geophilidae
(

; 

; 

).

The genus 

Schendyla
Bergsøe & Meinert, 1866

includes small or very small mostly European geophilomorphs. The species of this genus are characterized by two relatively large, separate coxal pores opening ventrally along the lateral margin on each side of the last sternite, as well as by ultimate legs with rudimentary claws or without claws (for a more detailed diagnosis of the genus, see 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). 

have listed 21 species as valid, mainly with an European distribution.

